entries.name: congruent
entries.condition_description: The color and word names match

entries.name: incongruent
entries.condition_description: The color and word names conflict with one another

entries.name: neutral
entries.condition_description: The word is not a color name

entries.name: Go trial
entries.condition_description: Trials on which a go stimulus is presented and the subject is expected to respond

entries.name: Stop trial
entries.condition_description: Trials on which a stop signal is presented at some delay (stop-signal delay) following the go stimulus, and the subject is expected to stop

entries.name: Go trials
entries.condition_description: Trials on which the stimulus is in the go category

entries.name: Stop trial
entries.condition_description: Trials on which the stimulus is in the stop category

entries.name: 0-back
entries.condition_description: A condition requiring stimulus matching but not working memory

entries.name: 3-back
entries.condition_description: A condition requiring memory for stimuli occurring 3 stimuli back

entries.name: Target
entries.condition_description: The stimulus to be responded to

entries.name: Nontarget
entries.condition_description: Any stimulus other than the target

entries.name: 1-back
entries.condition_description: A condition requiring memory for stimuli occurring 1 stimuli back

entries.name: 2-back
entries.condition_description: A condition requiring memory for stimuli occurring 2 stimuli back

entries.name: 3-back
entries.condition_description: A condition requiring memory for stimuli occurring 3 stimuli back

entries.name: no delay
entries.condition_description: No delay between initial presentation and probe

entries.name: delay
entries.condition_description: Probe presentation follows a delay after initial presentation

entries.name: Matching
entries.condition_description: The word and picture refer to the same concept

entries.name: Non-matching
entries.condition_description: The word and picture refer to different concepts

entries.name: Segmented blocks
entries.condition_description: None

entries.name: Unsegmented blocks
entries.condition_description: None

entries.name: Difficulty Level 1
entries.condition_description: All three stimulus dimensions must match

entries.name: Difficulty Level 2
entries.condition_description: Only two stimulus dimensions must match

entries.name: Difficulty Level 3
entries.condition_description: Only one stimulus dimension must match

entries.name: First category
entries.condition_description: The first category presented in the series

entries.name: Subsequent categories
entries.condition_description: Categories presented after the first in the series

entries.name: Perseverative errors
entries.condition_description: Errors that involve perseveration on the previously acquired set

entries.name: Nonperseverative errors
entries.condition_description: Errors that do not involve perseveration on the previously acquired set

entries.name: Failure to maintain set
entries.condition_description: Loss of the correct sorting rule during performance

entries.name: Congruent
entries.condition_description: Both body and head belong to the same animal

entries.name: Incongruent
entries.condition_description: Body and head belong to different types of animals

entries.name: Switch trial
entries.condition_description: Those trials on which subjects are required to switch from one task to another

entries.name: Repeat trial
entries.condition_description: Those trials on which subjects are required to repeat the same task that was performed on the previous trial

entries.name: Words
entries.condition_description: Valid words in the testing language for which the correct response is "Yes"

entries.name: Pseudowords
entries.condition_description: Pronounceable letter or phoneme strings which do not form a valid word in the testing language.  The correct response is "No"

entries.name: Consonant letter strings
entries.condition_description: In imaging studies (as opposed to purely behavioural expts) strings of consonants are often used as a nonlexical control condition because they do not engage the reading system to the same extent

entries.name: Fixation
entries.condition_description: A "baseline" condition when no letter string stimulus is presented and no response is expected

entries.name: Successful Stop Trial
entries.condition_description: A trial on which a stop signal is presented at a delay following the go stimulus, and the subject successfully withholds their response

entries.name: Unsuccessful stop trial
entries.condition_description: A trial on which a stop signal is presented at a delay following the go stimulus, and the subject fails to withhold their response

entries.name: delay period distractor task
entries.condition_description: an optional task performed during the delay period between target presentation and the response cue; tasks examples : number subtraction, word categorization

entries.name: sensory modality
entries.condition_description: This task is overwhelmingly performed with visual stimuli with a visual saccade response, however, a haptic version performed blind is described in Park & Holzman 1996.

entries.name: Successful stop trial
entries.condition_description: Stop trial on which subjects successfully inhibit

entries.name: Junk trial
entries.condition_description: A go trial on which subject failed to respond or responded incorrectly

entries.name: Probabilistic classification trials
entries.condition_description: Trials on which the subject classifies items

entries.name: Go trials
entries.condition_description: Trials on which a go stimulus is presented and the subject is expected to respond

entries.name: Stop-critical trial
entries.condition_description: Trials on which a stop signal is presented at some delay (stop-signal delay) following the go, and the stimulus is the critical stimulus, meaning that the subject is expected to stop

entries.name: Stop-noncritical trial
entries.condition_description: Trials on which a stop signal is presented at some delay (stop-signal delay) following the go, and the stimulus is the non-critical stimulus, meaning that the subject is not expected to stop

entries.name: Word
entries.condition_description: Pairs of real english words

entries.name: Pseudoword
entries.condition_description: Pairs of pseudowords

entries.name: meaningful
entries.condition_description: actions are common gestures

entries.name: meaningless
entries.condition_description: actions are novel, and have likely not been seen or performed by the participant before

entries.name: antisaccade
entries.condition_description: eye movements away from the fixation point

entries.name: prosaccade
entries.condition_description: eye movements toward the fixation point

entries.name: forward
entries.condition_description: participant repeats a string of digits in the order they were presented

entries.name: backward
entries.condition_description: participant repeats a string of digits in the reverse order, beginning with the last digit presented

entries.name: control pump
entries.condition_description: The participant pumps a control balloon which has no reward associated with it

entries.name: explosion
entries.condition_description: the balloon bursts and the participant loses all gains for the trial

entries.name: short form
entries.condition_description: 27 points, subjects match possible faces to one picture, the last seven questions use pictures different poses

entries.name: long form
entries.condition_description: 54 points, subjects complete the short form plus an additional nine questions with the pictures using alternate lighting and poses. Each picture has 3 possible matches during this portion

entries.name: copying test
entries.condition_description: participants copy pictures or geometric objects

entries.name: size match
entries.condition_description: participants judge whether two objects presented side-by-side are the same size

entries.name: length match
entries.condition_description: participants judge whether two objects presented side-by-side are the same length

entries.name: orientation match
entries.condition_description: participants judge whether two objects presented side-by-side are shown with the same orientation

entries.name: position of gap match
entries.condition_description: participants judge whether two objects presented side-by-side have a gap in the same position

entries.name: overlapping figures test
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to identify all the objects in pictures containing overlapping figures

entries.name: object decision
entries.condition_description: participants are shown pictures and asked to identify whether the object could be real or is unreal

entries.name: minimal feature match
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to select a picture that is the same as the original picture, but the saliency of the objectâs most distinctive feature is reduced

entries.name: foreshortened view
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to select a picture that is the same as the original picture, but the object's principle axis is foreshortened

entries.name: drawing from memory test
entries.condition_description: participants draw images varying in complexity from simple shapes to complex objects like faces

entries.name: picture naming
entries.condition_description: participants identify the names for pictures presented. Pictures are generally words used infrequently

entries.name: immediate recall
entries.condition_description: 16 words from four categories are presented to the participant, who is then asked to recall as many as possible in 5 consecutive trials

entries.name: interference
entries.condition_description: a list of other words is presented, and the participant is once again asked to recall the initial 16 words

entries.name: long recall
entries.condition_description: after 20 minutes have passed, the participant is again asked to recall as many words as possible from the original list of 16

entries.name: recognition trial
entries.condition_description: some researchers include a recognition trial at the end of the test, in which the participant is shown a list of words and asked which ones were on the original list

entries.name: same images
entries.condition_description: participants view 6 faces in a random order, then are given 3 forced-choice tasks per face they have seen, in which 2 distractor faces are added and the participant must choose which face they have seen before

entries.name: novel images
entries.condition_description: participants complete a forced-choice task as in the same images condition, but the original 6 faces are now shown in a different way (different lighting, new facial expression, etc.)

entries.name: novel images with noise
entries.condition_description: the participants complete a novel images forced-choice task, with Gaussian noise added

entries.name: ratio
entries.condition_description: each trial has different ratios of one color to the other, affecting the probability of selecting the right color for the token

entries.name: stimulus
entries.condition_description: a subject must watch for a stimulus to be presented in the way it was shown to them before the test, then must react by pressing a button

entries.name: non-stimulus
entries.condition_description: a subject is watching for a stimulus, but some other shape/picture/object is shown

entries.name: right hand
entries.condition_description: subjects are instructed to identify a stimulus or set of stimuli by pressing a button with the right hand

entries.name: left hand
entries.condition_description: subjects are instructed to identify a stimulus or set of stimuli by pressing a button with the left hand

entries.name: risky option
entries.condition_description: a choice that has a low probability of reward, but a higher reward than the non-risky option

entries.name: non-risky option
entries.condition_description: a choice that has a high probability of reward, but the reward is lower than in the risky option

entries.name: conditioned stimulus
entries.condition_description: a stimulus is presented that the subject has no instinctive response to, but the researcher hopes to create an automatic response to by pairing it with the unconditioned stimulus

entries.name: unconditioned stimulus
entries.condition_description: a stimulus that the subject has a natural, instinctive reaction to ( stimuli associated with pain, noise, fear, and reward are often used)

entries.name: descending
entries.condition_description: bets start high and decrease over time

entries.name: meditation
entries.condition_description: participant performs meditation of a specific subtype

entries.name: ascending
entries.condition_description: possible bets start low and increase over time

entries.name: formulating sentences subtest
entries.condition_description: participant is asked to use a specific word or phrase correctly in a sentence to describe a picture

entries.name: recalling sentences subtest
entries.condition_description: participant is asked to repeat a sentence

entries.name: sentence structure subtest
entries.condition_description: participant responds to sentences of varying difficulty and structure

entries.name: concepts and directions subtest
entries.condition_description: participant is asked to follow directions that become increasingly difficult and cover a range of language concepts

entries.name: word classes subtest
entries.condition_description: participants must identify how words relate to each other (synonyms/antonyms, types, etc.)

entries.name: word structure subtest
entries.condition_description: assesses participants understanding of morphology

entries.name: semantic relationships subtest
entries.condition_description: only administered to children 9 years and older, assesses ability to understand semantic relationships

entries.name: sentence assembly subtest
entries.condition_description: only administered to children 9 years and older, participant is given words or phrases and asked to construct sentences using them

entries.name: Stimulation at PT-0.7Â°C
entries.condition_description: Heat stimulation at pain threshold minus 0.7Â°C

entries.name: Stimulation at PT-1.0Â°C
entries.condition_description: Heat stimulation at pain threshold minus 1.0Â°C

entries.name: hider
entries.condition_description: the subject hides an object and is encouraged to mislead the experimenter or other participant about where the object is hidden

entries.name: guesser
entries.condition_description: the experimenter or another participant hides an object and clearly tries to decieve the subject about where the object is hidden. In this task the experimenter is trying to ascertain whether the subject has the theory of mind to identify deceptive intent in others.

entries.name: valid
entries.condition_description: a subject is given a syllogism and asked to complete it or, if complete, to judge whether it is logically sound

entries.name: invalid
entries.condition_description: a subject is given an illogical syllogism and asked to judge whether it is logically sound

entries.name: positive feedback
entries.condition_description: the participant chooses a box containing a prize

entries.name: negative feedback
entries.condition_description: the participant chooses the devil box and loses all previous gains

entries.name: immediate memory copy
entries.condition_description: in this version of the digit/symbol coding test, participants are shown a list of digits and symbols and immediately asked to write down the symbols that correspond to a list of digits

entries.name: general memory copy
entries.condition_description: in this version of the digit/symbol coding test, participants are given time to study a list of digits and symbols and, after a period of time, asked to write down the symbols that correspond to a list of digits

entries.name: verbal recall (people test)
entries.condition_description: participants are shown picures of people with names and occupations (or other information) attached. They are asked to recall the names when prompted with the occupation

entries.name: visual recognition (doors test)
entries.condition_description: participants view pictures of doors. They then are presented with groupings of doors, each containing one from the studyied photos and 3 distractors and asked to identify the familiar door

entries.name: visual recall (shapes test)
entries.condition_description: participants copy line drawings that resemble crosses, then they are asked to redraw the shapes from memory

entries.name: verbal recognition (names test)
entries.condition_description: participants view a list of names. They then are presented with groupings of names, each containing one from the studyied list and 3 distractors and asked to identify the familiar name

entries.name: congruent
entries.condition_description: the participant is shown a stimulus flanked by some congruent image (the same letter or number as the stimulus or arrows pointing in the same direction as the target stimulus)

entries.name: incongruent
entries.condition_description: the participant is shown a stimulus flanked by incongruent images (different letters or numbers or arrows pointing in the opposite direction)

entries.name: emotion detection
entries.condition_description: participants must indicate when the current faces emotion matches the emotion of the face presented n previously

entries.name: identity detection
entries.condition_description: participants must indicate when the current picture is of the same person as presented n previously

entries.name: rhythm tap
entries.condition_description: subject must tap a button each time they hear a tone or see a light flash, which is presented in a consistent rhythm. Then, they must continue tapping in this rhythm after the stimulus has ceased

entries.name: time tap
entries.condition_description: subject must tap a button as many times as possible in a period of 10 seconds. Usually repeated trials are administered and an average score is obtained.

entries.name: emotion manipulation
entries.condition_description: some words on the list have neutral meaning, while other words have highly emotional content

entries.name: category list
entries.condition_description: words on the list, even if organized randomly, come from distinct categories of association so the subject can group them together as a memorization strategy

entries.name: Transformation plates
entries.condition_description: plates are designed so that a person with deficient color vision will report a different digit than someone with normal color vision

entries.name: Vanishing plates
entries.condition_description: plates are designed to that a person with deficient color vision will not see any digits, while people with normal color vision will report some digit

entries.name: Hidden Digits plates
entries.condition_description: plates are designed so that a person with deficient color vision will report seeing a digit, while people with normal color vision will not

entries.name: Contamination/Cleaning
entries.condition_description: questions that assess whether the participant has abnormal standards of cleanliness or abnormal negative feelings associated with uncleanliness

entries.name: Checking
entries.condition_description: questions that assess whether the participant rechecks things that have been checked before, or checks things after certainty should already have been attained

entries.name: Slowness
entries.condition_description: questions that assess whether the participant takes longer than necessary to perform common tasks

entries.name: Doubting
entries.condition_description: questions that assess whether a participant requires an unrealistic amount of perfection or underestimates their ability to adequately perform tasks or make moral decisions

entries.name: Comprehension
entries.condition_description: subjects are played music and tested to see if they processed it, remembered it, or had the same auditory experience as others

entries.name: Production
entries.condition_description: subjects are asked to play or sing music

entries.name: Uncued
entries.condition_description: The subject is not shown a cue prior to the appearance of the stimulus

entries.name: Congruent Cue
entries.condition_description: A cue appears before the target stimulus. This cue is in the same location as the target stimulus (a location cue) or pointing in the direction of the target stimulus (an orientation cue).

entries.name: Incongruent Cue
entries.condition_description: A cue appears before the target stimulus, but in another location or orientation.

entries.name: Word
entries.condition_description: participants are presented with a real word

entries.name: Morphologically Decomposable Pseudowords
entries.condition_description: participants are presented with pseudowords whose structure contains morphemes that commonly exist in their language

entries.name: Morphologically Non-decomposable Pseudowords
entries.condition_description: participants are presented with pseudowords that do not have morphological structure

entries.name: Semantically correct
entries.condition_description: participants view sentences that are semantically correct and would make sense in everday speech (e.g. "Did the visitor that admired the plants leave the wallet in the room?")

entries.name: Semantically anomalous
entries.condition_description: participants view sentences that are semantically incorrect and would not make sense (e.g. "The boys admired the curly, new car of the secretary in the office.")

entries.name: Semantically associated items
entries.condition_description: participants view items that have some semantic association (e.g. "car" and "truck")

entries.name: Semantically unrelated items
entries.condition_description: participants view items that have no strong semantic association between them (e.g. "shirt" and "airplane")

entries.name: Congruent Cue
entries.condition_description: Participants view stimuli that are pointing in the same direction as the visual field they appear in, or participants press a button that resembles the stimulus or visual field (i.e. pressing a right arrow on a keyboard when a right-facing arrow appears, or the stimulus is in the right visual field)

entries.name: Incongruent Cue
entries.condition_description: Participants view stimuli that are pointing opposite the visual field they appear in, or the participants press a button that is opposite the stimulus direction or visual field (i.e. pressing a left arrow on a keyboard when a right-facing arrow appears, or when the stimulus is in the right visual field)

entries.name: 0-back
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to identify the spatial location of the dot in the current picture

entries.name: 1-back
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to identify the spatial location of the dot presented 1 picture previously, or indicate whether the current dot matches the position of the dot in the previous picture

entries.name: 2-back
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to identify the spatial location of the dot presented 2 pictures previously, or indicate whether the current dot matches the position of the dot in the picture presented 2 previously

entries.name: 3-back
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to identify the spatial location of the dot presented 3 pictures previously, or indicate whether the current dot matches the position of the dot in the picture presented 3 previously

entries.name: Trait Anxiety
entries.condition_description: this half of the questionnaire evaluates how the participant feels in general

entries.name: State Anxiety
entries.condition_description: this half of the questionnaire evaluates how the participant feels at the moment. This half is more likely to change with re-administration of the questionnaire

entries.name: congruent
entries.condition_description: the word is printed in the color that its name suggests (e.g. "yellow" printed in yellow ink)

entries.name: incongruent
entries.condition_description: the word is printed in a different color than its name suggests (e.g. "yellow" printed in red ink)

entries.name: Plausible Sentences
entries.condition_description: participants view sentences that are grammatically correct and plausible as real sentences

entries.name: Implausible Snetences
entries.condition_description: participants view sentences that are grammatically incorrect and implausible as real sentences

entries.name: Single Number
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a specific number each time it appears on a printed page with random sequences of numbers

entries.name: Single Geometric Form
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a specific symbol or drawing each time it appears on a printed page with random sequences of geometric forms

entries.name: Single Nonsense Letter
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a single, specific letter each time it appears on a printed page with random sequences of letters

entries.name: Gestalt Figure
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a complex figure each time it appears on a page with a random sequences of similarly constructed complex figures

entries.name: Single Letter
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a single, specific letter each time it appears on a printed page with random sequences of letters. Unlike the nonsense letter subtest, this test utilizes real letters from the alphabet of the participant's first language

entries.name: Single Letter in Syllable Context
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline all syllables containing a specific letter on a page of random sequences of syllables.

entries.name: Two Letters
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline two different, real letters each time they appear on a printed page with random sequences of letters

entries.name: Sequence of Geometric Forms
entries.condition_description: a page is filled with different orders of four geometric shapes. The participant is asked to underline the symbols when they occur in a specific order (e.g. triangle, then cross, then crescent, then circle)

entries.name: Four-Letter Nonsense Syllable (Unpronounceable)
entries.condition_description: a page is filled with random collections of syllables containing no vowels, and must underline a specific nonsense syllable (e.g. fsbm) each time it appears

entries.name: Four-Letter Nonsense Syllable (Pronounceable)
entries.condition_description: a page is filled with random collections of syllables containing vowels, and must underline a specific nonsense syllable (e.g. funp) each time it appears

entries.name: Four-Letter Word
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a specific four-letter word each time it appears on a page filled with random sequences of other four-letter words made up of the same letters as the target word

entries.name: Unspaced Four-Letter Word
entries.condition_description: participants are asked to underline a specific four-letter word each time it appears on a page filled with random sequences of other four-letter words made up of the same letters as the target word. Unlike the Four-Letter Word subtest, this subtest does not include spaces in between the four-letter words

entries.name: Single Number (Second Time)
entries.condition_description: participants repeat the first subtest, but search for a different number this time

entries.name: Congruent Cue
entries.condition_description: a visual cue appears in the same place as the target will appear, but slightly early

entries.name: Incongruent Cue
entries.condition_description: a visual cue appears before the target does, but in a different location

entries.name: RMW
entries.condition_description: participant is shown words and asked to later identify which ones have been seen before

entries.name: RMF
entries.condition_description: participant is shown faces and asked to later identify which ones have been seen before

entries.name: Matrix Reasoning
entries.condition_description: assesses the fluid intelligence of the participant

entries.name: Block Design
entries.condition_description: assesses spatial abilities of participants

entries.name: Similarities
entries.condition_description: assesses semantic knowledge and verbal ability of the participant

entries.name: Vocabulary
entries.condition_description: assesses the vocabulary and lexical knowledge of the participant

entries.name: Information
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked questions to measure general knowledge

entries.name: Digit Span
entries.condition_description: the participant is given a set of digits to repeat either forward or backward. The set grows each time until the participant can no longer correctly recall all the digits in order

entries.name: Vocabulary
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked to define 35 words

entries.name: Arithmetic
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked to solve 14 story problems with mental arithmetic

entries.name: Comprehension
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked 16 questions about social awareness

entries.name: Similarities
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked to say how seemingly dissibmilar items might be similar

entries.name: Picture Completion
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked to identify the vital missing detail in 20 pictures

entries.name: Picture Arrangement
entries.condition_description: the participant is given 10 sets of pictures and must arrange each set into a logical sequence

entries.name: Block Design
entries.condition_description: the participant mut assemble blocks to match pictures of designs

entries.name: Digit Symbol
entries.condition_description: the participant use a key - which pairs each number with a symbol - to identify which digit matches the symbols they are presented with

entries.name: Object Assembly
entries.condition_description: the participant completes puzzles

entries.name: Vocabulary
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked to define words

entries.name: Information
entries.condition_description: the participant is asked questions to measure general knowledge

entries.name: Logical Memory
entries.condition_description: participants must recall or recognize elements from a short story

entries.name: Verbal Paired Associates
entries.condition_description: participants must recall or recognize a word when prompted by an unrelated word that was paired with it during the presentation of word pairs

entries.name: Designs
entries.condition_description: participants must recall visual details and spatial locations of designs

entries.name: Visual Reproduction
entries.condition_description: participants view a picture and reproduce it after it has been taken away

entries.name: Spatial Addition
entries.condition_description: participants manipulate visuospatial information in their working memory

entries.name: Symbol Span
entries.condition_description: participants must recall sequences of symbols, increasing in size with each correct completion

entries.name: perceptual identification
entries.condition_description: a word is presented extremely briefly (and often tachistoscopically) on a computer screen and the participant is asked to say the word aloud when they see it

entries.name: lexical decision
entries.condition_description: a string of letters is presented and the participant is asked to identify whether the letters form a word or not

entries.name: latency identification
entries.condition_description: words are presented that the participant is asked to read, but some words are very common and others are used infrequently

entries.name: primed identification
entries.condition_description: participants are shown words that are semantically or structurally similar to the target word before the target word, which they are asked to read, appears

entries.name: Trait Affect
entries.condition_description: how the participant would answer questions in general

entries.name: State Affect
entries.condition_description: how the participant would answer questions at the moment, or over the past few days

entries.name: Early Blind
entries.condition_description: subjects who have been blind since birth or before the acquisition of developed language and/or reading skills

entries.name: Late Blind
entries.condition_description: subjects who lost their sight after acquiring the ability to read non-braille text

entries.name: Initiation
entries.condition_description: participants were instructed to complete a series of 15 sentences (e.g., He posted the letter without a â¦.) using the contextually predicted word (STAMP)

entries.name: Inhibition
entries.condition_description: participants were instructed to complete a series of 15 sentences (e.g., He posted the letter without a â¦.) using totally unconnected words (e.g. BANANA)

entries.name: 0-back
entries.condition_description: participant is shown or read a list of letters and then asked to identify the last letter given

entries.name: 1-back
entries.condition_description: participant is shown or read a list of letters and then asked to identify the letter given 1 letter previously

entries.name: 2-back
entries.condition_description: participant is shown or read a list of letters and then asked to identify the letter given 2 letters previously

entries.name: 3-back
entries.condition_description: participant is shown or read a list of letters and then asked to identify the letter given 3 letters previously, or asked if the current letter matches the letter given 3 letters back

entries.name: cue onset asynchrony
entries.condition_description: different onset lags between the two cues (e.g., the auditory onset is 50ms after visual onset)

entries.name: cue onset asynchrony
entries.condition_description: different onset lags between the two cues (e.g., the auditory onset is 50ms after visual onset)

entries.name: neutral
entries.condition_description: the stimulus is a non-color word or nonword (e.g., "house" or "XXXX" printed in red ink")

entries.name: verum acupuncture
entries.condition_description: needles placed according to guidelines usually derived from traditional Chinese practice

entries.name: sham acupuncture
entries.condition_description: needles placed at locations not corresponding to guidelines

entries.name: No-switch trials
entries.condition_description: trials that are preceeded by trials of the same type

entries.name: Switch trials
entries.condition_description: trials that are preceeded by trials of the other task type

entries.name: Common animals
entries.condition_description: Animals that are frequent and commonly known (e.g., horse)

entries.name: Rare animals
entries.condition_description: Animals that are not commonly encountered or known (e.g., egret)

entries.name: Congruent
entries.condition_description: flanker items indicate same response as target

entries.name: Incongruent
entries.condition_description: flanker items indicate opposite response as target

entries.name: Neutral
entries.condition_description: flanker items do not indicate either response

entries.name: Cue: none
entries.condition_description: no cue precedes trial

entries.name: Cue: double
entries.condition_description: cue precedes trial but provides no information about the location of the upcoming stimulus

entries.name: Cue: spatial
entries.condition_description: cue precedes trial and can predict location of upcoming stimulus

entries.name: Target
entries.condition_description: An "X" that is preceded by an "A"

entries.name: Distractors
entries.condition_description: All other items (including the "A" and any "X" not preceded by an "A"

entries.name: Baseline
entries.condition_description: Stimulation at skin temperature

entries.name: Heat Stimulation
entries.condition_description: Stimulation at a temperature above pain threshold

entries.name: Body ownership
entries.condition_description: Synchronous paintbrush stroking of the occluded hand and the rubber hand elicits the illusion of the rubber hand being part of oneâs body.

entries.name: No body ownership
entries.condition_description: Asynchronous paintbrush stroking of the occluded hand and the rubber hand.

entries.name: Noxious stimulation
entries.condition_description: Painful stimuli (e.g. sharp tips) are delivered to the skin

entries.name: Non-noxious stimulation
